To create a stack data structure using an array, you can use the following approach:
1. Initialize an array to store the elements of the stack.
2. Add elements to the stack by pushing them onto the end of the array.
3. To peek at the top element of the stack, simply access the element at the array's last index (i.e., the index of the last element added to the stack).
4. To remove the top element from the stack, simply remove the last element from the array.

Here is some sample code to illustrate these steps:
```
// Initialize an array to store the elements of the stack
var stack = [null];

// Add elements to the stack
stack.push('apple');
stack.push('banana');
stack.push('orange');

// Peek at the top element of the stack
console.log(stack[stack.length - 1]); // Output: apple

// Remove the top element from the stack
stack.pop();
console.log(stack[stack.length - 1]); // Output: banana
```
In this example, we initialize an array `stack` to store the elements of the stack. We then add elements to the stack by pushing them onto the end of the array using the `push()` method. To peek at the top element of the stack, we simply access the element at the array's last index using the `[ ]` notation. To remove the top element from the stack, we use the `pop()` method, which removes the last element from the array and returns it.
